<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">How to Use the Fabric Conversion Chart</h2>



<p>It occurred to me that maybe you are a little confused or not sure how t=
his fabric conversion chart will help you. So, let me give you an example. =
 </p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Example #1:</h3>



<p>Let=E2=80=99s say your pattern calls for 2-3/4 yards of 44=E2=80=B3 wide=
 fabric. But, the fabric you=E2=80=99ve chosen for your project comes in 60=
=E2=80=B3 width. So, do you still need 2-3/4 yards of fabric? Based on the =
fabric conversion chart, you do not! You only need 2 yards of fabric. </p>



<p>How did I come to this conclusion? Well, take a look at the <strong>Fabr=
ic Width</strong> row and find the column labeled <strong>44-45=E2=80=B3</s=
trong>. Come straight down that column until you come to <strong>2-3/4</str=
ong> yards. Then in the same row as the 2-3/4 yards, go straight across unt=
il you=E2=80=99re under the <strong>60=E2=80=B3</strong> column and you=E2=
=80=99ll see <strong>2</strong> yards. </p>



<p data-slot-rendered-content=3D"true">So for a pattern that calls for 2-3/=
4 yards of 44-45=E2=80=B3 wide fabric, you=E2=80=99ll only need 2 yards of =
60=E2=80=B3 wide fabric. </p>
